Essay Brief 1 – The Evolutionary Origins of Social Consciousness
Over the past few millennia, humanity has been able to accomplish some truly amazing things, including inventing verbal and written language, building technological replicas of the human brains, and even figuring out that the speck of cosmic dust called earth actually orbits around a very large ball of gas and fire. But humanity owes all of our accomplishments to the formation of collective social consciousness and the beginning of social groups and civilizations where the collective consciousness could flourish. But when did these developments start and why?
Like anything else, all sociological ideas strong bases to hold themselves up. Fligstein and MacAdams call these bases microfoundations. As far as many sociologists can tell, the collective consciousness started to form roughly 50,000 years which were quickly followed by relics from undefined religious practices, such as burial. These two things were fueled by the advancing development of the neocortex in the brain as Maryanski and Turner describe in The Neurology of Religion. Because the collective consciousness is the source of groups in religion, it makes sense that the two developments in humanity coincide in the timeline. Maryanski and Turner make the point that not only was religion created for more practical reasons of helping a group stay together under a great sense being other than their animal themselves but it was created for safety proposes. The world is a very terrifying place and it is that fact as well as other parts to mirofoundations that fueled the need for sets of rules and beliefs.
  They study of mircofoundations provides a clear light for sociologists to discover more about the psychological and situational events that lead to the development of religion and ancient societies. The fact that the development of mirofoundations was marked with relics that are now recognized as religious, in the broad sense, describes just how much humanity needed to feel like they were in control. All of the societal progress that humanity has witnessed over the past 50,000 years will always be thanks to the development of the collective conscious.

Disproportionate Gender Representation in STEM Fields

Department of Sociology, University of North Carolina Wilmington
SOC 105-002
Professor Dr. Elliot
April 28, 2021












	Everyone associates different topics based off prior experience which leads to our categorizing it. This is how all living creatures learn and adapt to different situations that they are placed in, so they know how to appropriately respond. When individuals start to share similar mindsets and express them in an environment it creates a collective conscious which puts pressure on other individuals in that same environment. This is collective conscious and experience within it are prevalent for college students when they are deciding on what fields they want to enter. The environment, daily life, and interest in the field are factors that are all considered and create their own collective conscious within each discipline which will attract similar minded people. Another factor that is not talked about as much is gender, which most noticeably different among the science, technology, engineering, and math (STEM) fields. This paper looks to explain why a disproportionate number of men enter the STEM fields compared to their female counterpart as a result of the collective conscious, difference in exposure prior to college, and different responses to classes. These factors make it so women wanting to enter a male dominated field become more difficult due to a cycle that has lasted generations.
	The very first topic that was discussed in this sociology class was about the social consciousness and becoming aware of societies form. One author that elaborated on this was Emile Durkheim, who said that the collective conscious was formed from multiple people having the same values and ideas. The collective conscious this society formed could be viewed differently by other societies which means that a society can never be “correct”. It also puts a pressure on individuals that exist in it to conform to beliefs or methods practiced which may cause that individual to stray away from their true nature.
	This concept is applicable in the college collective conscious for when people decide which field they wish to spend their life working or researching in, especially in STEM. Getting a degree is seen as a necessity to get a successful future within modern society so more people are inclined to go to college than in previous generations. With the STEM fields being notoriously hard for people, poor grades are bound to happen eventually for the majority of those who choose to go down that path. One area that was studied was the response to failing grades in men compared to women. This study found that women were more likely to change their major from a male dominated STEM field compared to men, who were more inclined to still pursue that same major (Kugler, 2021). They also found that women in male dominated STEM fields were more critical and harsher of their grades which was a big influence for switching majors. The reason for more women switching their major more frequently was denoted to the fact that because it was already male dominated, they might not matchup with the field even if they were to graduate where men did not have this concern. 
	The knowledge of the field being male dominated made enough of an impact to dictate decisions on whether to give up, which is completely external of the individual. Just because a person fails an exam or class in their major does not mean that they would be a terrible fit for it as a career. Their value and what they can contribute goes beyond what a test says and should be better elaborated in the STEM fields. These women who change their majors could be seen as falling under the pressure of the modern collective conscious to some extent by choosing to conform to more traditional female fields. Some of these women might have a talent for the field if they were to explore it more, but the collective conscious goes against them their entire journey by telling them they are social deviants. In some instances, they might even be told by their peers that they should leave the male dominated field because a woman has no place in it.
	This trend of male dominated STEM fields can appear strange considering more women attend education institutions past high school. The common factor that most college students have is that they went to high school, which also influences career paths for many. With gender roles and beliefs existing in societies, high schools may limit the exposure of the STEM fields to women compared to men. Things such as clubs and elective classes also influence interests that last long term and can even turn into careers, so gender segregation outside the classroom also adds another reason for why men are pushed further towards STEM fields. Gender segregation starts early in society with kids being told by others what they are supposed to like due to their sex, which pushes them toward a certain direction in the future when they want to explore more options. By the time they reach high school they have been pushed far enough a certain way by parents, peers, and society that all the available options are not considered (Lewgie & DiPrete, 2014).
	This early gender segregation of interests leads genders down a path that the collective conscious tells them is ok for them to be interested and work in, rather than letting the individuality of each person shine through. This pressure that each person faces throughout life alters the individual to fit more of what society wants or expects from them, keeping them trapped in a cyclic collective conscious. Societies are made and structured so that they are not easily changeable because most of the people in it create the rules, and if a person does not follow them then they are socially deviant. While everyone is socially deviant to an extent, there are core values integrated in societies that have harsher punishments compared to others. The punishment in this case would affect social life through school which would then transitions into work life after. 
	The other side of this trend in STEM fields falls on the side of the men. Questions may be asked about why they would be drawn to STEM rather than other fields of study. One study done found that men are more naturally inclined to gravitate toward STEM compared to women at all levels of high school math proficiency (Mann & DiPrete, 2013). While both men and women were close among math and science levels in high school, more men chose to enter a STEM field when they got to college partially due to life goals which was surveyed. Another factor to be noted in this study was that on average women had higher verbal and communication skills, which is also another contributor to women branching out more towards non-STEM fields. There are a lot of other reasons why people choose to pursue one major over the other, whether it be what they want their future to look like, money, or even stereotypes about that field. All these factors cannot be monitored and taken into account each study, but correlations can be drawn from quantitative data that is observable.
	The impact the collective conscious played in this study was noticing that women were better at the communication and writing compared to men. If they feel they are good at something other people might not be as good at, they might be more inclined to go towards that direction to help benefit the overall society that the collective conscious puts pressure on. With some of these fields such as education, psychology, and fine arts being female dominated, more women may feel comfortable sticking in these fields and ok with the gender disparities. Having already late to no exposure to non-required classes in high school was also seen across all these studies, and another reason for not wanting to explore these fields due to stereotypes along with them.
	The mindset people have when it comes to picking careers also comes with stereotypes of how people in that society perceive that career. The opinions of those around them also would influence their decisions while in post-secondary education. The collective conscious puts images and beliefs into its society from the experiences of others which generate stereotypes. These stereotypes are not based off fact, but rather opinions that were created and accepted by others to generalize. Stereotypes in the case of gender roles are harmful because they limit a person’s mindset and put forth false information that look to keep traditional values even if they are harmful. The stereotyping in STEM can seem like the fields are gatekept in a way. More men have reportedly wanted to keep the STEM field traditional compared to women who also say there is more injustice done towards them because of their gender (Castaño, Lubiano & García-Izquierdo, 2020). With more women feeling something is wrong with the collective conscious and stereotypes for them, they are considered social deviants as they are in the minority of what the STEM collective conscious views as acceptable. With men setting this collective conscious, they have set the impression and stereotype throughout the rest of society and a larger collective conscious that STEM is for males. 
	Breaking out of this collective conscious cycle is no easy feat, considering it still exists today just as it has in the past. The society is the one that changes and sets the collective conscious so all generations within it must widely accept it. This change cannot happen overnight but incorporating social deviance slowly would be an effective method that would slowly break apart these stereotypes and lack of exposure in society today. Education in modern society has been pushed more than ever before, so all paths should feel open to those who wish to continue past high school. Asian society however is completely different than American society in the fact that they encourage more people to pursue education in STEM regardless of gender. They also have seen results that research conducted among the same gender is more productive than if the two were opposite genders (Yang & Shen, 2020). This research also mentions the idea that female educators in STEM are seen as role models and encourage the younger female generations to enter STEM fields. This implies that if The United States were to hire more female STEM teachers, that over time more women would enter the field and push future generations to do the same. This would help break the collective conscious that is built in America and be more inviting towards women who might have an interest in STEM but are told that they should not pursue it because of their gender. 
	The impact that the collective conscious has is what drives a society whether it be seen as helpful or a hinderance. It wants to punish social deviance and reward conformity towards what is seen as acceptable, and with men deciding the collective conscious among STEM fields it allows them to keep these fields male dominated. As a result of this image women do not get the exposure throughout high school and childhood that men do to the STEM fields, which allows this to continue from generation to generation. This process will continue to exist until stereotypes and beliefs about women in STEM change to be more accepting of them which will in turn allow more exposure at younger ages to consider a STEM career path. With more gender equality and involvement in the STEM there can only be progression in the field as a result, which should not be feared by society. Encouragement should be done for anyone expressing interest in STEM just as it is in China. Breaking gender stereotypes created by the collective conscious must also be destroyed the same way by making this current deviance the accepted for the future. Societies are constantly looking to improve themselves through the lens of the collective conscious and making things deviant, but sometimes what is considered deviant is what is needed to improve.

Final Sociology Paper - Racism and White Privilege
	Racism, Sexism, Homophobia, Ageism, etc.; these issues are and have been incredibly prevalent in society since before recorded history because of the us versus them dynamic, which is one that most people fall into when talking about groups or cultures different from their own. But how do each of these topics relate to each other? And how do societies begin to actively work to fix the damage done by these issues? In predominately white cultures in Europe and North America, the issue of white privilege is currently receiving a lot of attention due to more efforts made to expose and resolve issues of racism in western societies. Numerous studies have been done on racism and white privilege especially in the United States since it currently holds the position of hegemonic power in the world. One of the main difficulties in ending the power these issues have over society is that they are so deeply ingrained in society and government that to tackle one topic, it to have to deal with all of them. The issue addressed today is the presence and effects of racism and white privilege in current western society, how it is currently shaping the future of these cultures, and what has proven effective in changing how issues, like racism, are treated. 
	White privilege: this term is defined as “the set of social and economic advantages that white people have by virtue of their race in a culture characterized by racial inequality” by the online dictionary and thesaurus Merriam-Webster.com. The concept of white privilege is one that often makes people uncomfortable, mainly white people, and therefore is not an easy topic of conversation. Because white people do not perceive their inherent advantages as such, they do recognize that it affects every single racial and ethnic minority around them in an increasingly negative light. 
One distinction that should be made is that occasionally when used in discussion, the term white privilege can be confused with the term white supremacist, which is defined by Merriam-Webster.com as “a person who believes that the white race is inherently superior to other races and that white people should have control over people of other races”. While white supremacy in western culture is viewed as the more serious offense against racial and ethnic minorities, white privilege can be seen in almost every facet of western society; governmental institutions, education, housing, social media, etc. With regards to general society, white privilege can be seen in how minorities are treated by authority figures. A most recent example being the recently exposed cases of police brutality in the United States, including the murders of George Floyd and Brianna Taylor
While the United States is often at the forefront of the news when the topic of racism and white privilege comes up, most predominately white cultures still have these issues. Michael J. Mascarenhas talks about the intersection between white privilege, the environment, and racism, in Ontario, Canada in his work Where the Waters Divide: Neoliberal Racism, White Privilege and Environmental Injustice. None of these issues are singular events that can be solved individually, they have been integrated almost completely into each other. Mascarenhas illustrates how racism and environmental injustice go hand in hand through his research into the contemporary type of racism that Canadian and First Nation people are seeing today. He states that this new type of racism “thrives in highly racialized societies that espouse racial equality, but in which whites… will not tolerate either being inconvenienced in order to achieve racial equality, or be denied the full benefits of their whiteness”. (Mascarenhas, 8). 
In Mascarenhas’ study, he interviewed twenty-seven First Nation people, including two Chiefs, water treatment plant workers, and community activists. He observed that Each of them faced the same fundamental racism in their everyday lives and when white Canadian citizens felt that their “rights” were being threatened by the First Nation people, they used “two of the oldest racial stereotypes of Indigenous Peoples—lacking motivation and intelligence “to work to survive.” (Mascarenhas, 11). According to Mascarenhas, the difference between the two groups was that the shortcomings of the First Nation people were due solely to choices of the individual instead of results from a society organized around particular types of racism. 
The work Everyday Racism’ in a Culture of Political Avoidance: Civil Society, Speech, and Taboo by Nina Eliasoph takes a deeper dive into what racism looks like through the more focused channel of how people talk about racism and race in situations that are not specifically devoted to that topic. Eliasoph looks at the benefits of having race conversations in everyday life and how when people treat these topics with sincerity, but not awkwardness or fear, much more progress in communication can be made. Communication is indeed one aspect of daily life that most people do not understand the power of or how to properly use it. The question of why most white people find it difficult to discuss racism or race during normal social conversation is because most people can be classified as “passive bystanders”. (Eliasoph, 486). Similar to the situation that occurs when a large group of people see someone be attacked and do nothing because they believe that someone else will do something, passive “bystanders notice the action and do not actively support it but do not do anything to oppose it, either.” (Eliasoph, 486). 
In the conclusion of Eliasoph’s work, she broke down how each of the categories discussed in her work, beliefs, social structures, and conversation, were observed to either encourage or limit open dialogue about race. While personal beliefs did not impact the conversation as much as anticipated, the concept of polite conversation did inhibit people from speaking freely about racism. Eliasoph noted that when social structures, like school/education, asked people to not speak on their thoughts of race but rather question the types of speech surrounding racial topics that the conversation flowed much more freely and the thoughts were then uncovered with less resistance. The last topic Eliasoph tackled is the global side of the discussion. Since racism is so ingrained into every society and culture in one way or the other, talking about it also involves talking about many other issues in the world including sexism, homophobia, ableism, sex trafficking, the drug trade, police brutality, etc. and when people are uncomfortable talking able one, they will be uncomfortable talking about any of these topics. 
Color-Blind Racial Attitudes: Microaggressions in the Context of Racism and White Privilege by Jared Edwards tackles the issue of microaggressions. The term microaggression is used to describe “a comment or action that subtly and often unconsciously or unintentionally express a prejudiced attitude toward a member of a marginalized group (such as a racial minority)”. Edwards talks about the historical context of racism in the United States, beginning with the slave trade that took place predominately in the southeast of the country. Though the true history of overt racism began with the early colonizers and the continual slaughter of the Native Americans, most history books lead the race discussion with the peak of slavery after the revolutionary war. But, in continuation, Edwards also mentions the Internment camps used during World War Two for the mass imprisonment of Asian American people due to the discrimination and distrust of Asian people. 
In the conclusion of Edwards’ argument, he talks about how every culture, group, society, etc. is unique and if we try to ignore or wash over this fact, we will face our own downfall. The experience that each group and more specifically each individual has in life will be different than anyone or other group could experience. “However, when we choose to truly explore our differences and really see others with their identities and experiences intact, then we can move toward true acceptance and valuation of diversity.” (Edwards, 15). 
The concept of true and complete acceptance of all differences while comforting on some levels is realistically impossible, and Edwards does address this unnamed concept of a utopia. This statement is backed through Color-Blind Racial Attitudes, otherwise referenced as CoBRAs, which Edwards defines as “the values expressed by those who claim to see all people as the same without acknowledging, or even noticing, racial identity” (Edwards, 12). However, CoBRAs and white privilege meet at an interesting point, because if people are completely blind to the differences of the minority groups around them, whether racial, sexual, or gender groups, then they hold to the same bases of the concept of white privilege; They will not be able to recognize the disadvantages that the other groups face and the challenges that they have to overcome. Like any controversial matter, education and honest discussion are the most effective tools for changing our perspectives. 
In conclusion, while western culture has made great pushes towards racial and gender equality in recent years through the activism and work of the people in these cultures, there are millions of more steps to take forward. None of these issues are new, but all are extremely important for every person to be educated in. Like the discussions of racism mentioned at the beginning of this essay, discussion about differences between different individuals or groups is not a comfortable one. Problems including white privilege and white supremacy are so securely rooted in the culture and society of the United States that to undermine these structures would be to destabilize the foundation of western social order. The reality of racism and sexism is that they are so ingrained into the world, that in order to wholly disassemble them, there will have to be a complete restructuring of every government and social concept.

The Power Elite Perpetuates White Privilege 

	The “power elite” makes up only a small percentage of the U.S. population. It is the rich socialites, Corporate executives, and prominent think tank members. These few people control a majority of all decisions made by political leaders. They use their money and influence to control the classes below them. Political leaders are not included in this “power elite,” as they are the main ones asking these elites for support for their campaigns. This makes them borderline puppets that the “power elite” use to push their agenda. 
	White privilege is a system developed in the United States as a means of justifying slavery and discrimination. It is extremely subtle in the ways it supports white people over other racial groups. Some examples of white privilege would be a white man being more likely to get a job over a minority or white people being put in “nicer” neighborhoods than other minorities. These practices further segregate races while giving white people an unfair advantage in life. 
	Some argue that it is on the part of white people themselves to tear down the workings of white privilege. Others contest that it is not their fault for being born white. Therefore, they have no obligation to fight that agenda. Looking to the power elite for an answer in this contest leads one to believe that they are the ones controlling it. A majority of the power elite consists of white men. The very people that white privilege serves are the ones with the most power to end it. The power elite controls all the policies that systematically promote white privilege. 
	Both these concepts share the promotion of people based mainly on birth right rather than by working for their spot. In the case of the “power elite” nepotism is a huge factor in who is in the “in” group and who is out. If someone is the child of a wealthy pharmaceutical CEO, odds are they will be invited to the same social events as his father when he hits the right age. This helps to condition their brain to promote the same culture for themself when they inevitably take control of their family's estate. It’s all about building up the foundation that protects themselves. When it comes to white privilege, it is a lot broader who is in the “in” group and who is out. Every white person in America is in the “in” group. Being born white is not nearly as exclusive as being born into money, but there are still a good amount of benefits that come with it. There is also the opportunity for motivation to keep the system in place. So, there is very clearly the process of elite white people to keep both systems in place to secure their high standings in the world. They do this by first protecting their position as elites, then using that power to keep white privilege as a system in place. 
	In comparison, white privilege is a much less direct process than holding power as the “power elite” is. Gaining and perpetuating white privilege is a very subconscious process. It can be summed up as being born white and reaping the benefits. The main workings of white privilege are just general prejudices deeply ingrained in the collective consciousness of the general population. Gaining and perpetuating the process as a “power elite” involves a lot of careful planning and luck. The lucky part is being born into the position and the careful planning is the lobbying you do to political leaders to keep yourself safe. 
	Real life examples of both these concepts can be found in high level office jobs across America. The diversity levels of high level jobs across America are so low that there are actual laws in place to try and even out the graph. This shows how white privilege perpetuates an advantageous life situation for white people. Some can argue that white people work for, and earn that spot. Even so, they have lives that are systematically designed for them to make it to the top. The “power elite” live for these high ranking office positions. These are not jobs like receptionists or printers. These are the board directors who sit for the boards of multiple different companies just to ensure the success of them all. 
	These two concepts are important to one another to stay afloat. White privilege gives the “power elite” a safety net to keep themselves in positions of power. While the “power elite” manage policies to maintain their own position and the systematic reproduction of white privilege. To tear down this horrible accumulation of power it takes white people to recognize their own privilege and for people to recognize where the power in our country is actually located. People need to bond together to tear down the “power elite” currently dictating our lives.

Graded Essay 4
	Since the dawn of humanity and the civilizations that they built, there has been inequality between groups. These inequalities were split down many social lines like gender identity, sexuality, ethnicity, etc. but one of the most common and still existing inequalities that humanity faces today is the effects of income inequality. In western society, income is equal to power and social standing, therefore whoever has the most money has the most influence in society. But, the role of technology is the fate deciding factor in how social standing and inequality affect humanity in the future.
In conclusion, since the 1% of society are almost in control of western civilization through their financial gains, it would be easy for them to monopolize the rest of society by buying out the technology companies that they do not already own in order to control the personal data that everyone else willing submits to these companies. In the opinion of Harari, the only way to prevent this from happening is through the regulation of data ownership. The best way to move forward with that plan is to educate the populous and use the power posses by the majority to stop the 1% from completely controlling their lives.

Mantsios states in the very beginning of his work that people do not like to talk about social classes, at least they do not like the connotations that come with some of the terms about their class. But, when a new name or more “gentle” term is applied to the group, everyone is more willing to talk. On the other hand, people are coming to recognize that the title of one’s class, whether it is economic or gender specific etc., they are no indicative of a person’s inherent worth. This idea is most definitely not new, but something that must be reintroduced to each generation. In continuation, the basic summary of Domhoff’s piece is that power and financial prowess will always go hand in hand. While this statement is true in many aspects of contemporary American society, the physical obtainment of money is not longer what people want to see. Society is beginning to judge those by not if they have money, but what they do with it. The truth is that people are seeing that bad people with a lot of money but no support are not going to get very far. Money is an arbitrary thing, and once the collective decides that a certain person’s wealth, no matter how much, is going worth respect, the finances lose all grounds.  
In regards to both of the readings, nothing is as simple as society likes to believe. One can poses an exorbitant amount of money, but if they do not command the respect of their peers and society, they hold very little power. The classes that people are defined away into continually change but each new generation must come to their own understanding of that these classes actually mean and what their generational relationship with intrinsic value is going to be. Yes, both reading make excellent points, but society is a living organism that will always change and adapt to the surrounding influences.

As humans we are naturally social being. Social interactions play a big part in how we identify and form our view of self. It is a fundamental need to feel like we belong and have intimate relationships with others. With the emergence of social media, you can be connected with thousands of others at a click of a button. This might sound like a useful tool, but it has its consequences.
	You would think in a world with social media we would feel more connected, but this is not the case. It has actually done the opposite; people feel more alienated than ever. This is because hundreds of online friends cannot provide you with the same feeling of belonging as a small intimate offline group can. We are becoming more disconnected by using social media as the main way to communicate and interact with each other. In order for us to feel like we belong it has to stem from the offline world. The body and self, interact and affect each other. To take away physical sense and the body from social interaction plays part in why online relationships are not able to provide you with the same feelings.
	Social media is a slippery slope. If we want to create meaningful relationships and feel like we belong we have to stray away from social media. People don’t realize the drastic affect social media can have our sense of self and should be educated on it.

Essay Brief 10
	When thinking of past worlds, you tend to greatly understand the reason behind them, why they were fought, what was gained. Modern wars? Not so much. If asked why the United States was involved in World War Two, the answer would be simple, to fight the Nazis; but if asked why the United States is fighting Iraq, most Americans would draw a blank. In chapter eleven of 21 Lessons For The 21st century, Harari depicts how much war and its reasons have changed over the years; much like the concept of rationalization which driven humans away from their roots.
	According to Harari, wars used to make sense politically; the United States fought Mexico for land, Japan grew more powerful as it fought China and Russia, and Britain became the Earth’s top empire through tiny wars all across the planet. These wars were successful, they had purpose, the United States grew by over 2.3 million square kilometers. This has changed though, wars in the Middle East are not successful and there are no clear winners or a purpose. As society grew and we modernized what had meaning, we also modernized war. Much like mostly everything in society, war has become a commodity; it has lost its meaning and purpose and now serves capitalism. Back in the premodern age, the only money you made was through the land you captured, but now its through profits on guns, machinery, and instruments used to cause more war; no one wins this way, war just continues. Just as society has been modernized, war has also been rationalized. 
	Harari examines premodern wars to modern wars, proving to his readers how war has been modernized into a commodity to feed the growing economy and money hungry elites. War is no longer about gaining land and growing your empire but gaining money so war can continue with no clear winner or goal.

	Throughout all of history there has been a struggle for power whether it be for an individual, group, or organization. This power does not come without pushing others down, and can be seen by examples of slavery, racism, or other types of prejudice. Groups such as African Americans, Asians, Native Americans, and women have had to push against being denied basic human rights in America along with being socially outcasted because of a feature they cannot control. Even in the modern day it is discussed about if there is true equal opportunity for everyone and whether certain groups are targeted for actions more than others in instances of applications, policing, and discrimination.

	Race has no basis in genetics whatsoever; it is entirely socially constructed. Just because race is not in our DNA does not mean the effects of it are not real. The meaning of slavery has changed over time; slavery used to be a period of bondage that an ancient person might pass through; today, when we think of slavery, we picture the enslavement of Africans in the United States. Slavery has been transformed into a racial issue over time and has triggered widespread racism all across the globe. Europeans created the idea of race to differentiate between those who did and did not look like them. This idea of different races separated and belittled certain groups of humanity, making them appear not even human anymore. Categories such as ‘savage’ for Native Americans, ‘subhuman’ for Africans, and ‘white’ were created, instilling the idea of race. These categories separated groups of humans by skin color and dehumanized those of darker skin. By claiming Africans as ‘subhuman,’ whites were able to strip them of their humanity and treat them as animals because that was how they were seen: like animals. As Europeans immigrated over to America, they took their ideas of race with them, developing an entirely new culture created by racism. As industrialism grew in America, so did the need for inexpensive labor; the Americans turned to the ‘subhumans’ in Africa. Whites kidnapped and sold Africans like animals, forcing them into slavery. Dark skin became an easy identifier for whether someone was a slave or not. The whites justified their enslavement of Africans with religion, economics, and science. They claimed that this race of subhumans could only be led from sin by a white master and that science proved that people of darker skin were not humans. These erroneous fundamentals helped shape and build American culture and society; the United States of America is founded on racism. 
Although Americans have come an incredibly long way from slavery, racism is still very much so prevalent in our society. American racism is no longer involves slavery or blunt dehumanization, but unjust inequalities not noticed by most. Things such as jobs, education, and luxury are catered more towards white Americans, leaving African Americans struggling. Yes, white Americans do have to deal with struggle and loss, but that pain will never be a result due to the color of their skin. As harsh racism of the past has begun to fade away, a new form of racism is taking its place: white privilege. White privilege is the advantages given to a white person due to their society or culture being founded or controlled by race. For many white people, the advantage they have due to their skin color is hard for them to comprehend and see. Often, white people are dismissive of the idea of white privilege and like to pretend it does not exist. The dismissal of white privilege makes it stronger and harder to fight. The more people who can recognize and understand their privilege, the more likely it is that this form of racism can be eliminated. Making racism illegal will not stop it; the best way to prevent racism is to exploit the racists that what they are doing is wrong and how it is wrong. Only by recognizing that the United States was built off racism and that white privilege thrives in society today; we will be able to take more steps of getting rid of racism completely. White privilege is a modern-day form of socially constructed racism to provide unfair advantages to those with white skin. 
In class, we studied how racism and slavery began and evolved over time; with no roots in genetics, racism was completely socially constructed. Humans created race to dehumanize other humans with different skin colors. This allowed for the white race to gain power over other races and exploit them for labor. White people labeled those with darker skin complexions as animals and inhuman to justify their horrible mistreatment and racism. Slavery and other extreme forms of racism may no longer be present in the United States, but racism still exists in America. The United States of America’s society and culture was founded on racism and that the white race is superior. These ideas are still structuring American society today, even with the advances taken to eradicate racism and establish equality for all. White people are still given unfair advantages in American society due to their skin color. Things such as work, power, and education are unfairly leaned in favor of white people, making it extremely hard for people of color to access these things. White privilege is an existing system within American society the promotes and upholds racism. It encases the idea that white people will never have to deal with struggles or tragedies due to the color of their skin. Society created white privilege to keep its old racist structure in tack while the idea of equality for all became more widespread. 
The concept of white privilege is often denied or misunderstood by white people. They can see that people of color are struggling but they look at themselves to see that they are also struggling. Due to their own struggle, white people tend to think that they cannot possibly have an advantage over anyone because they are struggling too. These people fail to comprehend that they are not struggling due to the color of their skin. White privilege is not saying that white people have never had to deal with struggle; it is saying that white people have never dealt with struggle due to the color of their skin. Whites often feel that white poverty is neglected “in order to portray poverty as a problem of black and brown” people (Blacksher). It is beliefs like that which drive white people from accepting that white privilege exists. The “deflection, discomfort, and denial of such advantages have been called white fragility,” which is when white people are unable or unwilling to recognize or accept that they have an advantage due to the color of their skin (Blacksher). White fragility dates back to when white people used science, religion, and economics to justify their poor treatment of people of color. Saying something along the lines of ‘white privilege does not exist, I am just as poor as he is’ is just as much as a dismissal of racism as ‘it does not matter, those are animals, not people’ is. By refusing to accept the existence of white privilege and American roots in racism, white people prevent the uprooting and eradication of racism.
Although not all white people have open arms to accepting the concept of white privilege and its existence, some white people have. Studies have found as white people have been more exposed to the advantages provided to them due to race, feelings of “guilt and shame are common reactions,” (Pinterits). Many white people have been able to come to terms with their own privilege and accept that they are advantaged because of their skin color. Instead of white fragility, they associate with white guilt. Although white people alive today are not responsible for creating racism and American society, with failure to recognize their privilege, they must maintain it. After conducting her study, Pinterits was able to determine that different white people had “various behaviors to address white privilege and engage in anti-racism and social justice work.” This shows that not all white people are unable to come to terms with their own white privilege and that some are willing to make a change. Recognizing white privilege is one of the first steps towards gaining total equality. As a white person being able to not only see your own privilege but the privilege of others and the systems that maintain that privilege is fundamental. With that, you can use your privilege to call out unjust systems and behaviors in order to help people of color reach equality. Things such as white fragility and silence stunt the growth of anti-racism and prevent other white people from speaking out. By recognizing and speaking out about their white privilege, white people are able to help promote ideals of equality and fight the racist American society and culture put into place hundreds of years ago.
Eradicating white privilege in America is one of the first steps of ridding the United States of racism. As a country that was built and founded on racist beliefs and ideologies, it will take time to unravel all the hate and prejudice that has been intertwined into American culture. Still, if we contain to fight for equality for people of color and recognize our own privilege, we can end racism and build a better and more accepting society and culture for all humans to live.

The Western Ideal of Beauty and Its Impact on Black and Asian Women
	Beauty standards are challenging enough to meet, and can lead to negative self-esteem in all women. But declines in mental health, self-esteem, and self-worth have a  more serious impact on Black and Asian communities due to the added internalization of racism. Omi and Winant explain in Racial Formations about the beginnings of racism as an institution in society meant to establish a dominant race - White Europeans. The process of racialization resulted in a racial hierarchy in society, where white people were superior over other groups of color through socially-constructed meanings added to race. This “superiority” of the white race has translated over into beauty standards, as physical features associated with the ideal are Eurocentric. This leads to more problematic consequences for Black and Asian women, as they internalize these beauty standards and learn to dislike physical features associated with their race that they not only see in themselves, but also in other members of  their racial group. 
	This internalization of racism and beauty standards translates directly into how Black and Asian women approach and experience potential romantic relationships with members of different racial groups. This was investigated by a group of social scientists at the University of California, that interviewed a group of eighteen university students. A goal of the study was to gauge the impact of Western beauty standards and racism in media on interracial attraction. Scientists saw a common theme held by the majority of the sample, that supported that beauty standards portrayed through media heavily impact what racial groups are believed to be most attractive. The sample also concluded that through media perpetuation of Western beauty standards, white people are portrayed as more attractive and successful compared to minorities, who are usually portrayed in congruence with offensive racial stereotypes. Media also tends to portray white people more frequently than minorities, which also has an impact on how familiar people are with other racial groups (Silvestrini, 2019). These stereotypical and sparse portrayals of minorities in popular culture and media impact the public’s judgements and familiarity with different racial groups. This leads to internalized racism as people choose to not pursue relationships with other specific racial groups because of negative, preconceived personality traits associated with certain physical features. This internalized racism is even present among minority groups, especially in Black and Asian populations as their traits deviate more from the Eurocentric standard. These variations are common among the features of people who identify within populations due to interracial attraction. Those who come from mixed-race backgrounds are found to be more highly valued as potential partners in Black and Asian populations, because they are closer in resemblance to the Western model. Due to the role of beauty standards and internalized racism in interracial attraction, Black and Asian women may start to see themselves as undesirable romantically, which can further translate into feeling completely undesirable. 
	Besides the usage of cosmetics and forms of dieting, another way that women can change their appearance to conform is through cosmetic surgery. This is the most expensive form of physical alterations, but it has become more common, with the United States, South Korea, and Brazil being the leading nations in this industry. In a study performed by Dr. Alexander Edmonds from Britain and Dr. So Yeon Leem from South Korea, the relationship between plastic surgery and racial phenotypes were analyzed to explore popular procedures in different countries, and show that race can be measured. This research was conducted through interviewing surgeons in all three countries, and analyzing medical and historical literature about the initial purposes of cosmetic surgery. In their study, they highlighted different surgical procedures that were especially popular in all three nations. In the US, they found that rhinoplasties were very common among patients that wanted to elongate and thin their noses. Rhinoplasties are also very common in South Korea and Brazil, as well as higher rates of skin-lightening procedures (glutathione injections). Another popular procedure more specific to South Korea is the double-eyelid procedure, which is a surgery that adds a crease to the upper lid of the eye that changes the appearance of the Asian monolid. These cosmetic procedures all result in patients appearing more Western, as common features of the Eurocentric beauty model are a whiter skin-tone, a smaller and thinner nose, and double-eyelids. The researchers discovered, however, that on the surface, the marketing and methods used in plastic surgery do not advertise Westernization of features directly. While plastic surgery is initially meant to help individuals look more similar to Europeans, a term referred to as “passing”, that has changed over the years as more Black and Asian people have received procedures, or are of mixed-race. In the US and South Korea, reference images of plastic surgery have changed to better fit the race of the individual seeking a certain trait. This is due to the science of anthropometry, which centers on the study of measurements and proportions of the human body. Through the usage of anthropometric facial analyses, surgeons are able to integrate Western features more naturally into the faces of Black and Asian women, and therefore create more accurate reference images that do not utilize solely European or white models. Through the usage of anthropometry, the marketing message of the plastic surgery industry has changed from the concept of “passing” to building upon the natural beauty of Black and Asian women (Edmonds & Leem, 2020). While the shift in message and methodology within the plastic surgery industry says otherwise, the core of the cosmetic industry in these countries remains the same in its intentions. The plastic surgery industry still relays the message to women that their “imperfections” should be corrected to correlate with beauty standards. The existence of anthropometry also shows that race cannot solely be deemed a social construct. These differences in racial phenotypes are then medicalized, and operated on - providing a substantial livelihood to plastic surgeons all around the world. The concept of a “meta-race” refers to the perfect mixture of African and Eurocentric skin tones and features. Cosmetic procedures are expensive and come with risks having to do with health complications and/or the surgeon who performs them. Overall, cosmetic surgery may stand to correct the superficial, but on the inside low self-esteem and internalized racism persist as Black and Asian women see their racial features as unattractive and abnormal.

Doing gender is a sociological concept by Candace West and Don Zimmerman that refers to the ways in which people actively perform their gender roles and behaviors in a social setting. The idea is that gender is not just the sex we were born as, but rather something we need to learn and perform to fit the societal role. During this process, people will actively participate in maintaining gender through their actions and interactions. We each learn to behave in accordance with what society deems normal for what a gender is and should be. People are ultimately rewarded through these norms and face negative backlash for failing to conform to these roles. Doing gender for a guy may be holding the door open for a lady or carrying the heavy groceries in from inside. Doing gender for a woman may be cleaning up around the house and being emotional support for men.
Hegemonic masculinity is another sociological concept that refers to the dominant form of masculinity that is idealized and reinforced in a particular culture or society. It represents the specific set of traits and behaviors that are socially valued and associated with being a "real man". Hegemonic masculinity is characterized by traits such as strength, toughness, and independence, as well as the ability to control and dominate others. Another important aspect of hegemonic masculinity is not showing emotion. This idealized form of masculinity is often associated with power and privilege, and it is reinforced especially through media, sports, entertainment, and society itself. Men who conform to this ideal are given status and respect, while those who do not adapt may face negative consequences such as discrimination or marginalization.
In Brian Stroudt’s “In or Out,” he conducts a social experiment in an all-boys prestigious private school called “Rockport.” The boys in Rockport are part of a culture that values traditional forms of masculinity, which includes traits such as physical strength, aggression, and toughness. In order to be accepted and respected within their peer group, the boys must conform to these masculine norms and expectations. They engage in activities such as playing sports, fighting, hazing, and bullying as a way of demonstrating their masculinity and asserting their social status. The boys often make sexist jokes with teachers and pick on the boys that aren’t “manly enough.” However, the study also reveals a few outliers in the school. For example, some boys show plenty of emotion and view woman as equals. Some reject the masculine ideology all-together. A few have even criticized the school for not learning the teachings of some famous women. Although, there are a few outliers, many support the hegemonic masculinity and culture created at this school and embrace it.

Therefore, fraternities attend community events, hold fundraisers for charity, and set a moral code on campus. These ideas promote doing gender in a way where men must be successful and prosperous. They must pass the test to the rest of the brothers. The higher-ups in the fraternity are also asserting their power over the newer members by making them do things for them through hazing. Each of these aspects are fundamental features of fraternity life, and they cater directly to the sociological concept of hegemonic masculinity.
Brian Stroudt’s social study of the Rockport boys in his “In or Out” is perhaps the most effective comparison to fraternity life. 	Before colonization took the world by storm, we lived in isolated groups that most the time shared the same color of skin, religion, and shared set of beliefs called our collective consciousness. Now days we live in diverse communities with varying religions, races, and beliefs. Despite this difference we still manage to share certain ideals and views as Americans. Then why are the same people that founded this country still the ones at the top? That does not sound like opportunity to me. This is because the white Europeans that founded this country established a system and society that operates and benefits their selves. Despite what we are taught to believe, we still live in a white European centric masculinist society. This is why whites benefit from something we call white privilege. 
	Erving Goffman says the self is made up of a structure of social encounters. White privilege plays a part in this development of identity. It has drastic effects on our society and the people in it. It results in a change of how whites and minority groups view themselves self, in different ways. Not only does white privilege change your sense of self, but it also actively prevents minorities from having equal opportunity as whites, while helping whites succeed. What does this mean and in what situations does white privilege take place? This can be from education, to politics, and also wealth disparities. As white privilege has become more of a focal point to our society in recent years, there is plenty of fresh research that applies to how white privilege brings down minorities while keeping whites at the top. Throughout this paper I will expand on how white privilege changes our sense of self, the structure of white privilege, and also how it affects certain groups when it comes to wealth education political action and other fields. 
	Whether we like it, or not racial and gender stereotypes are a part of our society’s collective consciousness. We might not realize it but subconsciously we have been taught to associate certain qualities with certain groups of people. These stereotypes play part in us “playing our roles”. In every social situation we identify the situation and try to fit a role. Since everyone is aware of how people expect them to act whether because the color of their skin or gender, people feel pressured to fit those stereotypes. Our sense of self changes based our reaction to these social reactions. For example, whites are handed unearned benefits at every turn. If a person is continually treated this way, it will have an effect on how they view themselves. This privilege can lead to unearned feelings of entitlement and superiority. This change of identity also takes place in minority groups in a different way. If you are taught your whole life that you are lesser than others just because of the color of your skin or your gender, you might start to believe it. This leads to subordination, self-hate, and an unjustified feeling of being inferior. This process is more subtle than it sounds, people might not even be completely aware they are being treated differently or the effect it has on their sense of self. The fact we are becoming more aware of white privilege is already a good indicator that we are headed in the right direction. Even so our collective consciousness of shared beliefs is deeply rooted into our society and will take a long time to make a permanent positive change.
	In class we talked about the Matrix of domination. Where there are people being oppressed there will also be oppressors. There are three main levels of oppression that people can experience: the level of personal biography, group or community oppression, and then systemic oppression. White privilege is an example of systematic oppression towards minorities and women. White women fall into an interesting group of being an oppressor and being oppressed simultaneously.  Another interesting group to look at is women who are also minorities. They are systematically oppressed not only because their skin color but also because they are women. Nobody has it harder than women of color in our society. Knowledge plays a huge role in how oppression operates. People who are less knowledgeful and educated are more easily influenced and taken advantage of. At points in history both minorities and women were denied education. This lack of knowledge and keeping these oppressed groups uneducated fosters subordination. Till this day these groups are denied a voice and equal attention. Our society focuses on the power elite white men, this gives them more control and a bigger voice. One example of this “attention” is how media and news stations tend to only care and report when something happens to a white person. If we want to change how our society oppresses women and minorities, we have to start giving them central attention and an equal voice. 
	There are endless examples and situations in which white privilege takes place. There are also plenty statistics to back these claims of unequal treatment. White privilege is involved in wealth disparities, health disparities, lack of equal education, unfair political action, unequal incarceration, and among many more. When it comes to wealth disparities there is a huge gap in pay between white men and non-white men. For example, Black women are on average paid 21,000 dollars less than their white counterparts for the same job (NPWF 2018). Not only is there a pay difference but whites are more likely to get better jobs than minorities or women that are just as qualified. There are also distinct differences in healthcare between races. For example, “Black women in the United States are more likely to die from pregnancy or childbirth than women in any other race group” (NPWF 2018). Black women are also three to four times more likely to experience a pregnancy-related death than white women (NPWF 2018). Another place where minorities are put at a disadvantage compared to whites is our incarceration system. For example, “Black men constitute 6 percent of the US adult population but are approximately 35 percent of the prison population and are incarcerated at a rate six times that of white males” (Marit Rahavi 2014). Another staggering statistic when it comes to incarceration is that “US incarceration rates for white men are 678 per hundred thousand and 91 per hundred thousand for white women. The incarceration rate for black men is a staggering six times greater than white men, and almost three times higher than for black women” (Moser 2020)
	Even though we have made significant progress towards equality, we still have a long way to go. Whites continue to reap unearned benefits while minorities and women are continuously put at a disadvantage by our society. Through health disparities, wealth disparities, unequal incarceration rates, and in countless more situations. This treatment does not just prevent them from succeeding but it also affects their sense of self. Nobody deserves to feel like less just because the color of their skin or gender.  White privilege has been an issue for a long time and will continue to be one unless we make an effort from both sides to make a change. This entails giving racial minorities and women more attention and a bigger platform. We should also make an effort to get qualified women and racial minorities into positions of power, especially in the government. It will take active awareness, while accepting that white privilege is a real and relevant issue.
